==English==
=== Etymology ===
Eponymous of king Pyrrhus of Epirus, who suffered heavy losses while defeating the Romans.

==== Adjective ====
'''Pyrrhic'''
# a very costly [[victory]]; a victory in which the means [[outweigh]] the ends [''Note'': Almost exclusively used in the clichéd term "pyrrhic victory"].
:'''quotations''':
:*"Tough pensions regulation designed to protect employees in final-salary occupational schemes will prove a '''pyrrhic victory''' for unions and the government, a report warned yesterday." &mdash;''The Guardian'', October 6, 2005

=== Etymology ===
From the Latin ''[[pyrrhichius]]'' from the Greek ''[[pyrrhichios]]'' from ''[[pyrrhiche]]'' "a dance"
==== Noun ====
'''pyrrhic'''
# a [[metric]] [[foot]] with two short or [[unaccented]] [[syllables]]
==== Adjective ====
'''pyrrhic'''
# characterized by pyrrhics

